{
  "terms": [
    {
      "term": "Force",
      "simpleDefinition": "A push or pull exerted on an object, measured in Newtons (N).",
      "anchor": "Pushing a heavy conduit bundle across a floor.",
      "misconception": "Thinking force is the same as weight; weight is a specific type of force caused by gravity."
    },
    {
      "term": "Work",
      "simpleDefinition": "The energy transferred when a force moves an object over a distance (Force x Distance).",
      "anchor": "Lifting a 20kg motor up a 2-meter ladder.",
      "misconception": "Believing you are doing 'work' in the mechanical sense just by holding a heavy object still; work requires movement."
    },
    {
      "term": "Energy",
      "simpleDefinition": "The capacity or 'fuel' required to perform work, measured in Joules (J).",
      "anchor": "The total amount of 'juice' available to move a load.",
      "misconception": "Thinking energy and work are different units; they are both measured in Joules because work is just energy in action."
    },
    {
      "term": "Potential Energy",
      "simpleDefinition": "Stored energy an object has because of its position or state.",
      "anchor": "A heavy chandelier hanging from a ceiling before it is released.",
      "misconception": "Thinking an object must be moving to have energy."
    },
    {
      "term": "Kinetic Energy",
      "simpleDefinition": "The energy an object possesses due to its motion.",
      "anchor": "A spinning motor shaft or a falling hammer.",
      "misconception": "Confusing kinetic energy with speed; speed is a component, but kinetic energy is the resulting capacity to do work."
    },
    {
      "term": "Power",
      "simpleDefinition": "The rate at which work is done or energy is transferred (Work / Time).",
      "anchor": "How fast a winch can lift a cable to the top of a building.",
      "misconception": "Confusing power with energy; energy is the total amount, power is how quickly you use it."
    },
    {
      "term": "Efficiency",
      "simpleDefinition": "The ratio of useful output energy to the total input energy, shown as a percentage.",
      "anchor": "A motor that gets hot is losing energy as heat instead of using it for movement.",
      "misconception": "Believing a machine can be 100% efficient; in the real world, energy is always lost to heat or friction."
    }
  ],
  "anchorPhrases": [
    "Work = Force × Distance",
    "Power = Work ÷ Time",
    "Efficiency = (Output ÷ Input) × 100",
    "One Watt is one Joule per second"
  ],
  "misconceptionTargets": [
    "Work and Energy are both measured in Joules.",
    "Power is about speed, Work is about the total task.",
    "No mechanical system is 100% efficient due to heat loss.",
    "If the object doesn't move, no mechanical work has been done."
  ]
}

{
  "teachChecks": [
    {
      "title": "Force, Work, and Energy",
      "objective": "Define the relationship between force, distance, and the resulting work or energy stored/expended.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "In mechanics, everything starts with Force. Measured in Newtons (N), force is the push or pull exerted on an object. However, simply pushing against a wall doesn't count as mechanical Work. For work to occur, that force must move the object over a distance. We calculate this using the formula: Work (Joules) = Force (Newtons) × Distance (metres).",
        "Because work is essentially energy in action, both Work and Energy share the same unit: the Joule (J). Energy is the capacity to do work and exists in two main states. Potential Energy is stored energy based on an object's position, like a heavy cable drum sitting at the top of a hoist before it is released. Kinetic Energy is the energy of motion, such as a motor shaft spinning or a hammer falling. It is a critical distinction for electricians: if an object does not move, no mechanical work has been done, regardless of the force applied."
      ],
      "hint": "Remember that Work requires movement over a distance and is measured in the same units as Energy."
    },
    {
      "title": "Power and Efficiency",
      "objective": "Explain power as the rate of doing work and efficiency as the ratio of useful output to total input.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "While Work tells us the total energy used for a task, Power tells us how quickly that work is being done. In electrical and mechanical terms, Power is the rate of doing work. We calculate it by dividing the Work done by the time taken: Power (Watts) = Work (Joules) ÷ Time (seconds). One Watt is defined as exactly one Joule of energy transferred per second.",
        "When you look at a motor rating, you are seeing its power output capacity. However, no machine is 100% efficient. Some energy is always lost, usually as heat or through friction. Efficiency is the ratio of useful output energy to the total input energy. We express this as a percentage using the formula: Efficiency = (Output ÷ Input) × 100. For example, if a motor takes in 1000W of electrical power but only delivers 800W of mechanical power to a pump, it is 80% efficient. The missing 200W is not gone; it has been converted into wasted heat energy."
      ],
      "hint": "Power is about the speed of the task, while efficiency compares what you get out to what you put in."
    }
  ]
}

